  "text": "Restraint is another frequently used stressor to study opiate effects. It potentiated morphine analgesia [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and naltrexone blocked the action of morphine [CITATION_3] , indicating its opiate nature. Chronic naloxone~ however, appeared to produce an upregulation of the opiate receptors, because the antagonist potentiated morphine analgesia when given with restraint, resulting in an even greater potentiation than with either alone. The upregulation was only transitory, because a few days after its removal the naloxone no longer potentiated morphine analgesia [CITATION_4] .",
